<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How can I predict my puppy's adult weight?", answer: "The most reliable method uses breed-specific growth curves. Puppies of different size categories grow at different rates. By knowing your puppy's current weight, age in weeks, and breed size category, you can estimate what percentage of their adult weight they have already reached and calculate the projected adult weight. For example, a medium-breed puppy at 16 weeks has typically reached about 55% of their adult weight." },
  { question: "At what age do puppies stop growing?", answer: "The age at which puppies stop growing depends on breed size. Toy breeds (under 10 lbs adult) typically reach adult weight by 9-12 months. Small breeds (10-25 lbs) finish growing by 10-12 months. Medium breeds (25-55 lbs) reach adult size by 12-15 months. Large breeds (55-90 lbs) continue growing until 15-18 months. Giant breeds (90+ lbs) may not reach full size until 18-24 months." },
  { question: "How accurate are puppy weight predictions?", answer: "Breed-category growth curves are generally accurate within 10-15% for purebred puppies when the breed size category is correctly identified. Mixed-breed puppies are harder to predict because their adult size depends on the genetic contribution of both parents. Factors that can affect accuracy include nutritional status, health conditions, spay/neuter timing, and individual genetic variation within a breed." },
  { question: "What breed size category is my puppy?", answer: "Breed size categories by typical adult weight: Toy breeds (4-10 lbs) include Chihuahuas, Yorkies, and Pomeranians. Small breeds (10-25 lbs) include Beagles, French Bulldogs, and Cocker Spaniels. Medium breeds (25-55 lbs) include Border Collies, Australian Shepherds, and Bulldogs. Large breeds (55-90 lbs) include Labradors, Golden Retrievers, and German Shepherds. Giant breeds (90+ lbs) include Great Danes, Mastiffs, and Saint Bernards." },
  { question: "Do mixed breed puppies grow at the same rate as purebreds?", answer: "Mixed breed puppies generally follow similar growth patterns to purebreds of the same adult size category. The challenge is determining the correct size category when parentage is unknown. If you know one or both parents, their sizes are the best predictor. If not, a veterinarian can estimate adult size from paw size, bone structure, and current growth rate. DNA testing can also identify breed mix and predicted adult weight range." }
]) %>

