    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Puppy Weight Predictor</h2>
      <p>
        Our free puppy weight predictor estimates your puppy's adult weight using breed-specific growth curves derived from veterinary research. Enter your puppy's current weight in pounds, their age in weeks, and select the breed size category that best matches their expected adult size. The calculator instantly predicts adult weight, shows what percentage of growth is completed, and estimates how many weeks remain until full size.
      </p>
      <p>
        Knowing your puppy's predicted adult weight helps with planning for crate sizes, choosing appropriate food formulas, estimating future costs, and understanding when growth-related behaviors like chewing and boundless energy will begin to settle. It also helps veterinarians track whether a puppy is growing at a healthy rate.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>How Growth Curves Work</h2>
      <p>
        Puppies do not grow at a constant rate. Growth is fastest during the first few months and gradually slows as the puppy approaches adult size. Smaller breeds reach their adult weight sooner than larger breeds. A toy breed puppy at 16 weeks has typically reached about 72% of its adult weight, while a giant breed puppy of the same age has only reached about 37%. The calculator uses these breed-specific growth percentage curves to extrapolate from current weight to predicted adult weight.
      </p>

      <h3>Breed Size Categories Explained</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Toy breeds</strong> (4-10 lbs adult) include Chihuahuas, Yorkies, and Pomeranians — they typically finish growing by 9-12 months. <strong>Small breeds</strong> (10-25 lbs) like Beagles and French Bulldogs reach full size by 10-12 months. <strong>Medium breeds</strong> (25-55 lbs) such as Border Collies and Bulldogs mature by 12-15 months. <strong>Large breeds</strong> (55-90 lbs) like Labradors and German Shepherds continue growing until 15-18 months. <strong>Giant breeds</strong> (90+ lbs) including Great Danes and Mastiffs may not reach full size until 18-24 months.
      </p>

      <h3>Factors Affecting Growth</h3>
      <p>
        While growth curves provide good estimates, several factors can affect actual adult size. Genetics is the primary determinant — puppies from larger parents tend to be larger. Nutrition plays a role; overfeeding during growth can lead to excess weight but not larger skeletal size, while underfeeding can stunt growth. Early spaying or neutering may slightly affect final size by allowing growth plates to remain open longer. Health conditions, parasites, and stress can also impact growth.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How can I predict my puppy's adult weight?</h3>
      <p>
        Use breed-specific growth curves. By knowing your puppy's current weight, age in weeks, and breed size category, you can estimate what percentage of adult weight they have reached and calculate the projected adult weight.
      </p>

      <h3>At what age do puppies stop growing?</h3>
      <p>
        Toy breeds reach adult weight by 9-12 months. Small breeds finish by 10-12 months. Medium breeds by 12-15 months. Large breeds by 15-18 months. Giant breeds may not reach full size until 18-24 months.
      </p>

      <h3>How accurate are puppy weight predictions?</h3>
      <p>
        Growth curves are generally accurate within 10-15% for purebred puppies when the correct breed size category is selected. Mixed breeds are harder to predict due to genetic variation.
      </p>

      <h3>What breed size category is my puppy?</h3>
      <p>
        Toy: 4-10 lbs (Chihuahua, Yorkie). Small: 10-25 lbs (Beagle, French Bulldog). Medium: 25-55 lbs (Border Collie, Bulldog). Large: 55-90 lbs (Labrador, German Shepherd). Giant: 90+ lbs (Great Dane, Mastiff).
      </p>

      <h3>Do mixed breed puppies grow at the same rate as purebreds?</h3>
      <p>
        Mixed breed puppies generally follow similar patterns to purebreds of the same adult size. The challenge is determining the correct category. A vet can help estimate, or DNA testing can identify breed mix and predicted size.
      </p>

